Logical NOT Operator (!)

  • How it works
    • !value converts the value to boolean, then inverts it
    • truthy → false
    • falsy → true

  • if (!condition)
    • Runs only when condition is falsy

Common Falsy Values

  • false
  • 0
  • "" (empty string)
  • null
  • undefined
  • NaN

Practical Examples

  • Checking for empty string
    • const name = ""
    • if (!name)
      • This runs because "" is falsy

  • Checking number input
    • const age = 0
    • if (!age)
      • This runs because 0 is falsy
      • Problem: 0 might be valid, but treated as missing

  • Checking undefined
    • let user
    • if (!user)
      • Runs because undefined is falsy

Key Pitfall

  • !value does NOT mean "value does not exist"
  • It means "value is falsy"

Safer Alternatives

  • Check for null or undefined only
    • value == null
      • true for null and undefined

  • Check explicitly
    • value === undefined
    • value === null

  • For numbers
    • typeof value !== "number"

Mental Model

  • !value = “Is this value falsy?”
  • Not = “Does this value exist?”
